[38;5;141m> [0m{"verdict": "pass", "rationale": "chapter05.04-python-example.md provides a complete Python companion that maps directly to the six pseudocode steps in recipe 5.4 (ingest, normalize, submit, evaluate, persist+propagate, invalidate). Boto3 usage is correct: dynamodb resource with Table.get_item/put_item, s3.put_object with ServerSideEncryption='aws:kms', sqs.send_message with MessageAttributes, events.put_events with Source/DetailType/EventBusName/Detail, cloudwatch.put_metric_data with Namespace/MetricData, and a proper adaptive-retry botocore Config. Error handling is present (timeout vs. protocol-error branches with bounded retry, try/except around every AWS call with structured logger.warning/info, demo-mode fallback to in-memory stores) and is consistently commented for healthcare-specific rationale (PHI in 270/271, BAA, KMS, clearinghouse cost, latency budget, fail-open). The recipe pattern is demonstrated end-to-end via run_pipeline and run_demo with five exercised scenarios (primary-key match, stale-ID search fallback, TPA dependent with person code, Medicaid not-found, cache hit) plus a Phase 2 invalidation and Phase 3 re-resolution. There are no stub/placeholder implementations: the Jaro-Winkler, DOB/sex/address/SSN/member-ID comparators, composite scorer, threshold logic, cache TTL derivation, payer-config normalization, and event/queue routing are all fully implemented. The MockClearinghouse is an explicitly labeled, fully working substitute for a paid clearinghouse SDK (with primary-key, search-single, search-multiple, and not-found branches), not a stub; gap-to-production notes call out exactly what to swap in (real SDK, pyx12, ElastiCache, TransactWriteItems, Step Functions, KMS, VPC, CloudTrail). TODO comments reference governance/atomic-write follow-ups rather than missing functionality."}[0m[1G[0m[0m[?25h